{"type":"message","id":"f0008dba","parentId":"a4a796ff","timestamp":"2026-03-19T16:55:23.784Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The context monitor shows we're at 77% usage. The cron job is just monitoring, not automatically creating a new session. This seems to be a monitoring/cron job that just alerts about context usage. \n\nSince this is a cron job alert and not a user message, I should just reply HEARTBEAT_OK or provide a brief status. However, looking at the context - this appears to be a system cron event firing. The user (董事长) isn't directly asking me anything.\n\nLet me check - this is a cron job context monitor. The system is telling me context is at 77%. Should I just acknowledge or is there something more useful I can do?\n\nGiven the context is at 77% and climbing, and my role as 金融虾 (financial advisor), this seems like an informational alert. The cron job itself is designed to just monitor and alert. I should probably just note this internally and maybe create a summary for the user or just acknowledge.\n\nWait - this is coming through as a user message (the cron job message). I should respond to it. But what would be useful? The context manager skill should be handling this. Let me think about what a useful response would be:\n\n1. The alert level is WARNING (77% > 60%)\n2. It's suggesting to start a new session\n\nI could offer to start a new session or create a summary of the current context. But since there's no specific user question, I'll keep it brief and informative.\n\nActually, looking at the skill description for miliger-context-manager, it says it \"Monitors usage, triggers at 85% threshold, automatically creates new session with loaded memory. Zero user intervention required.\" So maybe at 77% it's not yet auto-creating a new session but just alerting.\n\nI'll provide a brief status update since this is a cron-triggered event.","thinkingSignature":"cf7c5e49a4c849059fc189781f825a6eb5c7acb40bd385fd9e53f